{"id": "duc04-testb-40:9#29", "contents": "In addition to discussing North Korea, Clinton and Kim also talked about the Asian financial crisis and the need for economic reform in South Korea. Clinton congratulated Kim on his efforts at economic reform, noting that interest rates had fallen and the currency had stabilized. However, he also pressed Kim to restructure the five huge conglomerates, or chaebols, that account for some 40 percent of the Korean economy. Clinton expressed impatience about South Korea's failure to act on the chaebols, and his advisor, Berger, described restructuring the chaebols as \"perhaps the most serious remaining problem in the South Korean economy.\""}
